Effect of the neighbourhood quality on the apartment rent¶

Introduction¶

The value of an apartment depends on more than the location and the characteristics of a apartment. It also depends on the neighbourhood and the mobility. The aim of this project is to analyse the quality of a neighbourhood and the effect on the apartment rent.

For example if an investor has a list of apartments which are available for sale he would probably only want to invest in an apartment that is located in a good neighboorhood. Evaluating the neighbourhood requires a lot of local knowledge or some research about it. If the quality of the neighbourhood could be evaluated by the foursquare data instead, this could save a lot of time and would help to evaluate the apartments automatically.

Data description¶

The foursuqare data is used to evaluate the quality of the neighbourhood. Therefore the following categories are used:

  • nearby public transportations
  • schools / universities
  • cultural venues
  • food venues
  • nightlife
  • nature and spare time

are analysed.

The apartment data consists of the apartment base rent and additional information like latitude, longitude, square feet etc.

Methodology¶

To analyse the neighbourhood of the apartments, the number of venues in each category are evaluated for each apartment. Afterwards, the correlation between number of venue and the average base rent per square meter is shown in a box plot, to get the average values and remove the outliers

Data preparation¶

At first, the latitude and longitude values needs to be edited

Analyse the data¶

First we visualize the data by showing the locations on the map of leipzig

In [399]:
from folium.plugins import FastMarkerCluster


address = 'Leipzig, DE'

geolocator = Nominatim(user_agent="leipzig_explorer")
location = geolocator.geocode(address)
latitude = location.latitude
longitude = location.longitude
print('The geograpical coordinate of leipzig are {}, {}.'.format(latitude, longitude))

fast_map_leipzig = folium.Map(location=[latitude, longitude], zoom_start=12)

# add all the point from the file to the map object using FastMarkerCluster
fast_map_leipzig.add_child(FastMarkerCluster(data= apartments_df[['lat', 'long','rel_baseRent']].values.tolist()))
fast_map_leipzig

The geograpical coordinate of leipzig are 51.3406321, 12.3747329.
Out[399]:

The map shows that the data has a good distribution of the apartments in Leipzig. There are more apartments in the center of Leipzig but the data contains apartments for all districts. Since some districts are more trending than others, which effects the apartment rent, we can analyse the average apartment rent for each district.

Therefore, the entries can be grouped by the district and the rent per square meter can be averaged.

In [369]:
avg_rent = apartments_df[{'rel_baseRent','obj_regio3'}].groupby(['obj_regio3'], as_index=False).mean()

Analyse the neighbourhood effect with foursquare¶

This section uses the foursquare api to analyse the neightbourhood of each apartment. Therefore, the venues for different categories are requested.

First, we analyse the public transportation possibilities for each apartment.

In [ ]:
apartments_df['transportations'] = 0
for index, row in apartments_df.iterrows():
    long = float(row['long'])
    lat = float(row['lat'])
    url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/explore?client_id={}&client_secret={}&ll={},{}&v={}&radius={}&limit={}&categoryId={}'.format(CLIENT_ID, CLIENT_SECRET, lat, long, VERSION, 500, 50,'4d4b7105d754a06379d81259')
    results = requests.get(url).json()
    if(len(results['response'])==0):
        continue
    number_of_stations = len(results['response']['groups'][0]['items'])
    print('There are {} transportation venues around.'.format(number_of_stations))
    apartments_df['transportations'][index] = number_of_stations

The graph show, that the number of transportation venues has small effect on the average rent of the apartments. Since most of the apartments have 2-5 transportation venues in the neighbourhood, the outliers are the most for no stations.

The next categorie is culture, since areas with more cultural venues should be more trending than others.

In [ ]:
apartments_df['culture'] = 0
for index, row in apartments_df.iterrows():
    long = float(row['long'])
    lat = float(row['lat'])
    url = 'https://api.foursquare.com/v2/venues/explore?client_id={}&client_secret={}&ll={},{}&v={}&radius={}&limit={}&categoryId={}'.format(CLIENT_ID, CLIENT_SECRET, lat, long, VERSION, 500, 50,'4d4b7104d754a06370d81259')
    results = requests.get(url).json()
    if(len(results['response'])==0):
        print("no results")
        continue
    number_of_venues = len(results['response']['groups'][0]['items'])
    print('There are {} culture venues around.'.format(number_of_venues))
    apartments_df['culture'][index] = number_of_venues

As expected, the number of cultural venues has an effect on the apartment rent. The graph also shows that the average rent per square meter stops increasing after 5-10 cultural venues but this could be caused by the low number of apartments with a high number of venues in the neighbourhood. Another interesting part in this graph are the outliers. The apartments with less or no cultural venues have lower outliers than the apartments with 5-10 cultural venues in the neighbourhood.

Discussion¶

All analysis show an increase of the average rent per square meter regarding to the number of the venues for a specific category. But not only the average rent has increased, but also the outliers often increase with the number of venues. The graphs also show that increase stops at a given value and even decrease in a few cases but thats probably because of the low number of samples. This should be further analysed with more samples to get more reliable results

All in all the analysis show that the foursquare data can be used for more precise prediction of the rent of a apartment besides the apartment specific characterics like number of rooms or square meter. It also shows that the rent differs from neighbourhood to neighbourhood.

Conclusion¶

This analysis shows that the neighbourhood has an effect on the average rent per square meter and that this effect can also be quantified and further be used as the other characteristics of an apartment to predict the rent.
